                        <th class="text-right">Amount</th>
                        <th class="text-right">% of Income</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody id="breakdownBody">
                    <!-- JS injected -->
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="brackets-section">
        <h2 class="panel-title">2026 Tax Brackets Table</h2>
        <div class="tabs" id="bracketTabs">
            <button class="tab active" data-target="federal">Federal</button>
            <button class="tab" data-target="provincial">Provincial</button>
        </div>

        <div class="brackets-grid" id="bracketsDisplay">
            <!-- JS injected -->
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
        <h2 class="panel-title" style="font-size: 2rem;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What are the Canadian federal tax brackets for 2026?</h3>
            <p>For 2026, the projected federal tax brackets are: 15% up to $58,809; 20.5% between $58,809 and $117,619; 26% between $117,619 and $182,329; 29% between $182,329 and $259,749; and 33% on income over $259,749.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How much is the Basic Personal Amount (BPA) for 2026?</h3>
            <p>The projected federal Basic Personal Amount for 2026 is approximately $16,611. This is the amount of income you can earn before paying any federal income tax.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is the difference between marginal tax rate and average tax rate?</h3>
            <p>Your marginal tax rate is the percentage of tax applied to your last dollar earned. Your average tax rate is the total tax you pay divided by your total income, which is always lower than your marginal rate due to progressive tax brackets.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are Canadian tax brackets adjusted for inflation?</h3>
            <p>Yes, both federal and provincial tax brackets (in most provinces) are indexed to inflation annually using the Consumer Price Index (CPI). This prevents 'bracket creep' where inflation pushes individuals into higher tax brackets without a real increase in purchasing power.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How much are the CPP and EI deductions in 2026?</h3>
            <p>For 2026, CPP base contributions are roughly 5.95% up to the max pensionable earnings limit, plus the CPP2 second ceiling contribution of 4%. EI premiums are 1.66% up to the maximum insurable earnings limit.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="methodology">
        <h2>Data & Methodology</h2>
        <p>The 2026 tax brackets, basic personal amounts, and payroll limits presented here are <strong>projected estimates</strong>. The Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) traditionally announces official indexation factors in November of the preceding year. We have applied a standard historical inflation indexation factor (~2.5%) to the finalized 2024/2025 CRA and provincial limits to generate these forward-looking estimates. Actual limits may vary slightly when officially finalized. This calculator focuses on standard employment income and standard basic personal amounts; it does not factor in RRSP contributions, self-employment, capital gains, or specific regional tax credits.</p>
    </div>

</div>
  <script is:inline>
document.getElementById('year').textContent = new Date().getFullYear();

    const taxData = {
      federal: [
        { rate: 0.15, threshold: 0 },
        { rate: 0.205, threshold: 58809 },
        { rate: 0.26, threshold: 117619 },
        { rate: 0.29, threshold: 182329 },
